==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Apsis
<hw>Ap"sis</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧p"s⟦icr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Apsides</plw>
<pr>(⟦acr⟧p"s⟦icr⟧*d⟦emac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <see>See <er>Apse</er>.</see>
<ety>[L. <ets>apsis</ets>, <ets>absis</ets>, Gr. <grk>"apsi`s</grk>,
<grk>"apsi^dos</grk>, a tying, fastening, the hoop of a wheel, the
wheel, a bow, arch, vault, fr. <grk>"a`ptein</grk> to fasten.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>One of the two points of an orbit,
as of a planet or satellite, which are at the greatest and least
distance from the central body, corresponding to the aphelion and
perihelion of a planet, or to the apogee and perigee of the moon. The
more distant is called the <xex>higher apsis</xex>; the other, the
<xex>lower apsis</xex>; and the line joining them, the <xex>line of
apsides</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>In a curve referred to polar
co⟦oum⟧rdinates, any point for which the radius vector is a maximum or
minimum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Apse</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Apsu</ent>⟦br⟧
